{
  "summary": "This paper proposes a two-step framework for annotation-efficient in-context learning with large language models, introducing vote-k, a novel graph-based selective annotation method that balances diversity and representativeness. Extensive experiments on 10 diverse NLP tasks demonstrate that vote-k significantly improves in-context learning performance, reduces annotation costs compared to finetuning, and enhances robustness, especially under domain shifts.",
  "strengths": [
    {
      "point": "Novel two-step framework separating selective annotation and prompt retrieval",
      "evidence": "The paper clearly defines and motivates a principled framework to study annotation efficiency in in-context learning, distinguishing between pre-test selective annotation and test-time prompt retrieval."
    },
    {
      "point": "Vote-k algorithm effectively balances diversity and representativeness",
      "evidence": "Vote-k uses a k-NN graph and iterative scoring to select examples that cover the data manifold well, outperforming random, diversity-only, and uncertainty-based baselines across multiple datasets."
    },
    {
      "point": "Comprehensive empirical validation across 10 diverse NLP datasets and tasks",
      "evidence": "Experiments include classification, commonsense reasoning, semantic parsing, dialogue state tracking, and code generation, showing consistent gains at different annotation budgets and model sizes."
    },
    {
      "point": "Demonstrated annotation cost reduction compared to supervised finetuning",
      "evidence": "Vote-k enables in-context learning to match or exceed finetuning performance with 10-100× fewer annotated examples, highlighting practical efficiency benefits."
    },
    {
      "point": "Robustness and stability improvements under domain shift and data sampling randomness",
      "evidence": "The method shows larger gains under domain shift and reduces variance caused by random unlabeled data sampling, making in-context learning more reliable."
    }
  ],
  "weaknesses": [
    {
      "point": "Insufficient discussion and empirical comparison with classical active learning methods",
      "evidence": "The paper does not evaluate or discuss classical AL methods like query-by-committee, BALD, or core-set selection, which combine uncertainty and diversity, limiting understanding of vote-k’s novelty."
    },
    {
      "point": "Lack of sensitivity analysis on k-NN graph parameter k and vote-k thresholds",
      "evidence": "No ablations varying k or vote-k scoring thresholds are provided, leaving unclear the robustness of the method to hyperparameter choices."
    },
    {
      "point": "Exclusive reliance on Sentence-BERT embeddings without comparison to alternatives",
      "evidence": "The paper does not justify or ablate embedding choices against raw LM embeddings, SimCSE, or task-specific embeddings, which may affect neighbor graph quality."
    },
    {
      "point": "Limited baselines for prompt retrieval strategies",
      "evidence": "Only random retrieval is compared; clustering-based or learned dense retrieval methods are not evaluated, making it unclear how much retrieval contributes to gains."
    },
    {
      "point": "Finetuning baselines lack experiments with robust training techniques on selected subsets",
      "evidence": "No experiments with curriculum learning, outlier filtering, or noise-robust optimization are conducted to fairly assess selective annotation benefits for finetuning."
    },
    {
      "point": "Annotation cost evaluation limited to example counts without real-world cost measures",
      "evidence": "No annotation time, cost per label, or annotator effort estimates are provided, reducing practical interpretability of cost savings."
    },
    {
      "point": "Insufficient details on domain shift scenarios and quantitative measures",
      "evidence": "Domain shift experiments lack dataset split descriptions, domain divergence metrics, and ablations by shift severity, hindering reproducibility."
    },
    {
      "point": "Reproducibility concerns due to missing annotation process details and code release",
      "evidence": "No information on annotator expertise, guidelines, quality control, or public code and hyperparameter settings is provided."
    },
    {
      "point": "Opaque description of vote-k algorithm without pseudocode or illustrations",
      "evidence": "Dense textual explanation without algorithmic pseudocode or diagrams reduces accessibility and implementation ease."
    },
    {
      "point": "Ambiguity in annotation budget reporting and example counts",
      "evidence": "It is unclear whether budgets are total or per class, complicating interpretation across datasets with varying class distributions."
    },
    {
      "point": "Scalability challenges of k-NN graph construction on large unlabeled pools not addressed",
      "evidence": "No discussion of approximate nearest neighbor methods or sampling strategies to handle large datasets is included."
    },
    {
      "point": "Applicability beyond NLP tasks and modalities not explored",
      "evidence": "All experiments focus on NLP; no discussion of extensions to vision, speech, or multi-modal tasks is provided."
    },
    {
      "point": "Limited analysis of performance gains relative to model size",
      "evidence": "No detailed study on how gains scale with model size or annotation cost trade-offs for smaller versus larger models."
    },
    {
      "point": "Insufficient analysis of vote-k’s impact on structured output tasks",
      "evidence": "No error breakdowns or detailed results on semantic parsing or dialogue state tracking compared to classification tasks."
    },
    {
      "point": "Interaction between selective annotation and prompt length constraints not analyzed",
      "evidence": "No study on how prompt length limits affect annotation budget benefits or retrieval strategies."
    },
    {
      "point": "Effect of annotation noise or label quality on vote-k performance not discussed",
      "evidence": "No robustness analysis or noise mitigation strategies are presented despite real-world annotation challenges."
    },
    {
      "point": "Computational cost and efficiency of vote-k compared to simpler baselines not quantified",
      "evidence": "Runtime, memory usage, and scalability comparisons are missing, limiting practical adoption insights."
    },
    {
      "point": "Impact of class imbalance on selective annotation not analyzed",
      "evidence": "No class-wise selection statistics or performance analyses to assess bias toward majority classes."
    },
    {
      "point": "Potential biases introduced by embedding-based selection not addressed",
      "evidence": "No discussion of linguistic style, topical, or distributional biases that embedding similarity might induce in selected subsets."
    }
  ],
  "questions": [
    {
      "question": "How does vote-k compare empirically and conceptually to classical active learning methods that combine uncertainty and diversity?",
      "motivation": "Understanding this would clarify vote-k’s novelty and whether classical AL techniques could be adapted for selective annotation in in-context learning."
    },
    {
      "question": "How sensitive is vote-k’s performance to the choice of k in the k-NN graph and the vote-k scoring thresholds?",
      "motivation": "Sensitivity analysis would inform robustness and practical guidance for tuning hyperparameters in different datasets or domains."
    },
    {
      "question": "Would alternative embedding methods improve selective annotation and prompt retrieval performance compared to Sentence-BERT?",
      "motivation": "Embedding quality directly affects neighbor graphs and retrieval; exploring alternatives could enhance generality and effectiveness."
    },
    {
      "question": "Can robust finetuning methods applied to selectively annotated subsets close the performance gap with in-context learning?",
      "motivation": "This would test whether selective annotation uniquely benefits in-context learning or if finetuning can also leverage it with proper training."
    },
    {
      "question": "What are the real-world annotation costs in terms of time and effort for vote-k selected examples compared to random selection?",
      "motivation": "Quantifying practical annotation cost savings is critical for adoption and deployment decisions."
    },
    {
      "question": "How scalable is vote-k to very large unlabeled pools, and what approximations or optimizations can enable its use in large-scale settings?",
      "motivation": "Addressing scalability is essential for practical application to large datasets common in industry."
    },
    {
      "question": "Does vote-k selection introduce biases in the annotated subset that affect fairness or coverage across linguistic styles or topics?",
      "motivation": "Understanding potential biases is important to ensure representativeness and fairness in downstream applications."
    }
  ],
  "scores": {
    "correctness": 3,
    "novelty": 3,
    "recommendation": "borderline",
    "confidence": 3
  }
}
